    • assertExceptionThrown

      @Deprecated public static void assertExceptionThrown(Runnable code, Class<? extends Throwable> exceptionClass)
      Deprecated.
      use assertThrows(Class, GWRunnable) instead.

      Asserts that the specified Exception (really, any Throwable) was thrown by the code encapsulated in a Runnable.

      For example: 
       assertExceptionThrown(new Runnable() { public void run() {
    agencyPaymentItem.reverse();
 } }, IllegalStateException.class);

      Will fail the test if the reverse() method doesn't throw an IllegalStateException.

      This'd be a lot nicer in Gosu with blocks.

      Parameters:
      code - a Runnable implementation with the code under assertion in the public void run() method
      exceptionClass - the class of the exception expected to be thrown in the code

    • assertExceptionThrown

      @Deprecated public static void assertExceptionThrown(String failureMessage, Runnable code, Class<? extends Throwable> exceptionClass)
      Deprecated.
      use assertThrows(String, Class, GWRunnable) instead.

      Asserts that the specified Exception (really, any Throwable) was thrown by the code encapsulated in a Runnable.

      For example: 
       assertExceptionThrown("Expected the exception because blah blah blah",
     new Runnable() { public void run() {
       agencyPaymentItem.reverse();
 } }, IllegalStateException.class);

      Will fail the test if the reverse() method doesn't throw an IllegalStateException.

      This'd be a lot nicer in Gosu with blocks.

      Parameters:
      failureMessage - the message that will be displayed if this assertion fails
      code - a Runnable implementation with the code under assertion in the public void run() method
      exceptionClass - the class of the exception expected to be thrown in the code

    • assertExceptionThrownWithMessage

      @Deprecated public static void assertExceptionThrownWithMessage(Runnable code, Class<? extends Throwable> exceptionClass, String expectedExceptionMessage)
      Deprecated.
      Refer Javadoc of assertThrows(Class, GWRunnable) for example of implementation to verify expected exception message

      Asserts that the specified Exception (really, any Throwable) was thrown by the code encapsulated in a Runnable and the message from the exception matches the expected String exactly.

      For example: 
       assertExceptionThrown(new Runnable() { public void run() {
    agencyPaymentItem.reverse();
 } }, IllegalStateException.class, "Oops");

      Will fail the test if the reverse() method doesn't throw an IllegalStateException or the message doesn't match "Oops."

      This'd be a lot nicer in Gosu with blocks.

      Parameters:
      code - a Runnable implementation with the code under assertion in the public void run() method
      exceptionClass - the class of the exception expected to be thrown in the code
      expectedExceptionMessage - the text of the exception message that needs to match exactly

    • assertThrows

      public static com.guidewire.testharness.assertion.ThrowableAssertionHelper assertThrows(Class<? extends Throwable> exceptionClass, GWRunnable gwRunnable)
      Asserts that the specified Exception (really, any Throwable) was thrown by the code encapsulated in a GWRunnable.

      For example:

      1. To assert a specified exception: 

       assertThrows(IllegalStateException.class, new GWRunnable() { public void run()  throws Exception {
    agencyPaymentItem.reverse();
 } } );
      Will fail the test if the reverse() method doesn't throw an IllegalStateException.

      2. To assert a specified exception with expected exception message 

       ThrowableAssertionHelper t = assertThrows(IllegalStateException.class, () -> agencyPaymentItem.reverse());
 t.message().isEqualTo(expectedExceptionMessage);
      Parameters:
      exceptionClass - the class of the exception expected to be thrown in the code
      gwRunnable - a GWRunnable implementation with the code under assertion in the public void run() method
      Returns:
      ThrowableAssertionHelper
      See Also:
      • assertThrows(String, Class, GWRunnable)

    • assertThrows

      public static com.guidewire.testharness.assertion.ThrowableAssertionHelper assertThrows(String failureMessage, Class<? extends Throwable> exceptionClass, GWRunnable gwRunnable)
      Asserts that the specified Exception (really, any Throwable) was thrown by the code encapsulated in a GWRunnable.

      For example:

      1. To assert exception and display user defined failure message if assertion fails: 

       assertThrows("Expected the exception because blah blah blah",
       IllegalStateException.class, () -> agencyPaymentItem.reverse());
      Will fail the test if the reverse() method doesn't throw an IllegalStateException.

      2. To verify contents of the message thrown: 

       assertThrows("failure message", ArithmeticException.class, () -> 1 / 0)
   .message().contains("div by 0");
      Parameters:
      failureMessage - the message that will be displayed if this assertion fails
      exceptionClass - the class of the exception expected to be thrown in the code
      gwRunnable - a GWRunnable implementation with the code under assertion in the public void run() method
      Returns:
      ThrowableAssertionHelper

    • assertMethodDeclaredAndOverridesBaseClass

      public static void assertMethodDeclaredAndOverridesBaseClass(Class myClass, String methodName, Class[] parameterTypes)
      Deprecated.
      If you're using this test, then you probably need to 1) remove the test and 2) remove the overriding behavior if a DM property is being overridden.
      Asserts that a method with methodName and parameterTypes exists on myClass, and that it does indeed override a method on a superclass. This assertion is especially useful in making sure overriden entity properties continue to be overridden and don't get lost (for example, during an entity refactor).
      Parameters:
      myClass - class name
      methodName - method name
      parameterTypes - method parameter types

      public static void assertBigDecimalEquals(String message, BigDecimal expected, BigDecimal actual)
      Uses BigDecimal.compareTo(BigDecimal) to determine if two BigDecimals are equal. Also, if one of the BigDecimals is null and the other is zero, this method considers them equal.
      Parameters:

      expected - expected value
      actual - actualy value
